  X6: =_xll.RiskOutput(X2)+AA109
  AA9: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Z9)
  AB9: =IF(AA9=1,_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Prob_Illness_Given_Infection),0)
  AD9: =$D9*AG$3
  AE9: =INT(AD9) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,AD9-INT(AD9))
  AF9: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+AE9)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+AE9)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)
  AG9: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,AF9)
  AH9: =IF(AG9=1,_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Prob_Illness_Given_Infection),0)
  AJ9: =$D9*AM$3
  AK9: =INT(AJ9) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,AJ9-INT(AJ9))
  AL9: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+AK9)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+AK9)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)
  AM9: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,AL9)

  EV21: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+EU21)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+EU21)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)
  EW21: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,EV21)
  EX21: =IF(EW21=1,_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Prob_Illness_Given_Infection),0)
  EZ21: =$D21*FC$3
  F21: =$D21*I$3
  FA21: =INT(EZ21) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,EZ21-INT(EZ21))
  FB21: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+FA21)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+FA21)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)
  FC21: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,FB21)
  FD21: =IF(FC21=1,_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Prob_Illness_Given_Infection),0)
  FF21: =$D21*FI$3

  DV29: =$D29*DY$3
  DW29: =INT(DV29) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,DV29-INT(DV29))
  DX29: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+DW29)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+DW29)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)

  FA43: =INT(EZ43) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,EZ43-INT(EZ43))
  FB43: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+FA43)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+FA43)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)
  FC43: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,FB43)
  FD43: =IF(FC43=1,_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Prob_Illness_Given_Infection),0)
  FF43: =$D43*FI$3
  FG43: =INT(FF43) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,FF43-INT(FF43))
  FH43: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+FG43)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+FG43)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)

  BX44: =IF(BW44=1,_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Prob_Illness_Given_Infection),0)
  BZ44: =$D44*CC$3
  C44: =_xll.RiskLoglogistic(LogLogistic_gamma, LogLogistic_beta, LogLogistic_alpha, _xll.RiskTruncate(5,800))
  CA44: =INT(BZ44) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,BZ44-INT(BZ44))

  D44: = C44*BAF/V
  DA44: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,CZ44)

  ED51: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+EC51)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+EC51)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)
  EE51: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,ED51)
  EF51: =IF(EE51=1,_xll.RiskBinomial(1,Prob_Illness_Given_Infection),0)
  EH51: =$D51*EK$3
  EI51: =INT(EH51) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,EH51-INT(EH51))
  EJ51: = MAX(1-EXP((GAMMALN(beta+EI51)+GAMMALN(alpha+beta)-GAMMALN(alpha+beta+EI51)-GAMMALN(beta))),0)

  D59: = C59*BAF/V
  DA59: =_xll.RiskBinomial(1,CZ59)

  BZ67: =$D67*CC$3

  CA67: =INT(BZ67) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,BZ67-INT(BZ67))

  EH106: =$D106*EK$3
  EI106: =INT(EH106) + _xll.RiskBinomial(1,EH106-INT(EH106))

--- FORMULAS ---
  D26: = Pathogen
  G26: =CONCATENATE("HOCKEY STICK data and calculations, Effluent ",Pathogen," (gc/L")
  K28: =(100-K27)/100
  K29: =(K27-50)/100
  D31: = Pathogen_Conc_in_Effluent_min
  E31: = Pathogen_Conc_in_Effluent_median
  F31: =0.5*(E31 + G31 +1/H31 - SQRT((G31-E31)^2 + 1/(H31^2) + E31*(2-8*K$28)/H31 + G31*(2-8*K$29)/H31))
  G31: = Pathogen_Conc_in_Effluent_max
  H31: =1/(E31-D31)
  I31: =2*K$28/(G31-F31)
  J31: =H31*(E31-D31)/2 + (H31+I31)*(F31-E31)/2 + I31*(G31-F31)/2
  K31: = _xll.RiskGeneral(D31,G31,E31:F31,H31:I31)/Pathogen_Method_Harmonisation_Factor

--- SAMPLE DATA (first 20 cells) ---
  B2: Explanation
  B3: The data (green cells) don't easily lend themselves to fitting to a  
  B4: particular distribution. So we use the RiskGeneral function in @RISK, for an empirical 
  B5: probability density function ("pdf"). To do so we use the constraint that the total area under the
  B6: pdf = 1. To satisfy this constraint we find the value of the 100P%ile (XP) given a user-supplied
  B7: value of P. This value is above the median. We also use linear interpolation between the pdf 
  B8: breakpoints (note that were we to join BD by a straight line we would over-estimate the median
  B9: and the frequency of most of the high values).
  B11: The algebra involves solving a quadratic, and this is the calculation sequence:
  B13: h1 = 
  C13: 2*0.5/(X50 - X0)
  B15: XP = 
  C15: {X50 + X100 + 1/h1 - SQRT[(X100-X50)2 + 1/h12 + (X50/h1)(2-8q) + (X100/h1)(2-8s)]}/2
  B17: h2 = 
  C17: 2*q/(X100 - XP)
  B19: As a check we can sum all the resulting areas and we get Ashould=1 = 1, as required. 
  B20: Finally, we use the RiskGeneral function, with the above table layout, to generate the random draws. 
  B21: In the box above we have chosen P = 0.95 (i.e., the breakpoint is the 95%ile). This seems appropriate given the usual (lognormal) form of 
  B22: distributions of microrganisms. Results check (using 1000 iterations: min = 597, 50%ile = 4999, 95%ile = 8222, max = 9751). Pretty good!
  B24: Note that the h2 equation in McBride (2005) has an X50 on the denominator, but that should be XP.

--- DATAFRAME SHAPE ---
  Rows: 31, Columns: 11

  B54: = F41
  C54: =F41
  B55: = G41*SQRT(E41)
  B56: = _xll.RiskNormal(BAF_mean,BAF_standard_deviation,_xll.RiskTruncate(1,100))

--- SAMPLE DATA (first 20 cells) ---
  A1: This material is based on the approach taken by Andrew Ball (ESR) in modelling shellfish doses in a model for the Waimakariri coast (for WDC).
  A2: I have made some changes however, as noted below.
  A4: LOCAL EDIBLE SHELLFISH AND PATHOGEN DOSE RECEIVED BY CONSUMERS OF RAW SHELLFISH
  A5: The presence and abundance of intertidal shellfish has been surveyed and reported by Kingett Mitchell (2003).  The tuatua (Paphies donacina), a filter-feeding bivalve 
  A6: mollusc, is the major species in this area and is the only one to attain edible size.  Tuatua ranged from 2-55mm in length, with a mean size of 14.7mm. However, the
  A7: average size is of little value because shellfish-gatherers tend to collect adult shells.  The size of adult tuatua was surveyed at several Pegasus Bay beaches during 
  A8: 1998 (Marsden, 2000).  The median shell lengths from Woodend, Spencer Park and Pines beaches were 67, 52 and 47mm respectively.
  A10: Tuatua feed by filtering out particles suspended in seawater.  Consequently, they can concentrate pathogens and other microorganisms present in seawater.  This
  A11: imposes a greater disease illness risk on  consumers of raw shellfish compared with recreational water users. To estimate the consumers' pathogen doses we must 
  A12: first estimate the meal size. Then in the absence of a survey of pathogens in shellfish, it is necessary to make an estimate of pathogen concentrations in shellfish. To 
  A13: do that we apply a "bioaccumulation factor (BAF)" to pathogen concentrations in the overlying seawater.
  A15: MEAL SIZE (grams)
  A16: An estimate of shellfish consumption was obtained from the raw data generated from the 1997 National Nutrition Survey (Russell et al., 1999). These data comprised 
  A17: estimates of daily intake from 98 consumers of shellfish, comprising individuals consuming mussels (57), oysters (21), scallops (15), pipi (4) and tuatua (1); paua and 
  A18: canned shellfish were excluded.  Quantities of shellfish were measured in terms of weight or volume, the latter being converted to grams on the assumption that the 
  A19: density of shellfish is very close to 1 g/mL (see histogram below).  Andrew Ball fitted by a loglogistic distribution with parameters b = 75.072, g = -0.9032, a = 2.2046. 
  A20: Running this with 1000 iterations we get minimum = 0.80, 1%ile = 8.27, 5%ile = 18.8, 50%ile = 74.1, 95%ile = 283, 99%ile = 596, maximum = 1748 g. While this
  A21: provides a good fit to the body of the distribution, the high tail value is unreasonable (the maximum meal size measured was 790 g). Also, Rose & Sobsey (1993) 
  A22: estimated that the likely average serving was based on a 60-240 g, meal comprising 612 shellfish of between 10 and 20g each in weight. So we trncate the 
  A23: distribution at 5 and 800 g. With 1000 iterations we get minimum = 5.5, 1%ile = 9.6, 5%ile = 19.4, 50%ile = 74.0, 95%ile = 270, 99%ile = 484, maximum = 786 g.

--- DATAFRAME SHAPE ---
  Rows: 66, Columns: 7
